          "label": "Sonnet 4.6",
          "content": "# B0D41ZMDPD — Sales Decline Analysis\n\n## Data Window\n- **Report Period:** 2026-03-09 to 2026-05-07 (60 days)\n- **Data Source:** Amazon Ads Product Report + Campaign Report (MAS-Tools account, US marketplace)\n- **Total Report Rows:** 13,009 (product attribution) + 1,095 (campaign performance)\n- **Rows for B0D41ZMDPD:** 236\n\n---\n\n## Product Overview\n\n| Field | Value |\n|---|---|\n| ASIN | B0D41ZMDPD |\n| Product | Fanttik T1 MAX Soldering Station |\n| Brand | Fanttik |\n| Category | Construction – Concrete & Metal Tools |\n| Avg. Sale Price | ~$60.54 |\n| Total Ad-Attributed Sales (60 days) | $234,300 |\n| Total Ad-Attributed Purchases | 3,870 |\n\n---\n\n## Advertising Campaign Phases\n\nThe T1 MAX was supported by campaigns organized in three distinct phases, revealing a clear performance degradation over time:\n\n### Phase 1 — SP Launch Campaigns (Started March 9)\n\n| Campaign | Spend | Sales | ROAS | Impressions | CPC | Conv. Rate |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| SP-T1 MAX-KW-A-solder | $17,875 | $77,224 | 4.32x | 1,364,053 | $1.71 | — |\n| SP-T1 MAX-Brands-solder | $6,035 | $51,188 | 8.48x | 625,972 | $1.12 | — |\n| SP-KW-T1 MAX-AMC-solder | $4,371 | $31,190 | 7.14x | 491,039 | $1.07 | — |\n| SP-T1 MAX-CAT-solder | $2,793 | $14,001 | 5.01x | 186,518 | $1.29 | — |\n| **Phase 1 Total** | **$31,074** | **$173,603** | **5.59x** | **2,667,582** | **$1.40** | **12.75%** |\n\n### Phase 2 — Keyword Expansion (Started March 14)\n\n| Campaign | Spend | Sales | ROAS | Impressions | CPC | Conv. Rate |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| SP-T1 MAX-KW-B-solder | $6,679 | $28,896 | 4.33x | 702,089 | $1.50 | 10.75% |\n\n### Phase 3 — Defensive/Retargeting Campaigns (Started April 7–27)\n\n| Campaign | Start | Spend | Sales | ROAS | DPV |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| SBV-T1 MAX-KW-横版-solder (video) | Apr 7 | $990 | $1,828 | 1.85x | 1,124 |\n| SD-T1 MAX-VCPM-本品浏览营销 (retargeting) | Apr 11 | $223 | $280 | 1.25x | 314 |\n| SB-KW-T1 MAX/S1PRO/S2PRO-Brands | Apr 19 | $475 | $2,233 | 4.70x | 960 |\n| SD-T1 MAX-CAT-VCPM (DSP category) | Apr 27 | $312 | $1,443 | 4.62x | 1,043 |\n| **Phase 3 Total** | — | **$2,000** | **$5,784** | **2.89x** | **3,441** |\n\n---\n\n## Key Evidence of Sales Decline\n\n### 1. ROAS Deterioration (Most Critical Signal)\nThe core SP campaigns (Phase 1) delivered **4.32–8.48x ROAS**. By Phase 3, newly launched campaigns achieved only **1.25–1.85x ROAS** — a 65–85% decline in advertising efficiency. This indicates the product can no longer convert clicks into sales at its original rate.\n\n### 2. CPC Inflation (+33%)\n- Phase 1 CPC: **$1.40/click**\n- Phase 3 CPC: **$1.86/click**\n\nRising CPC is a direct indicator of increased keyword competition. Competitors are bidding more aggressively on \"soldering station\" and related keywords, crowding out T1 MAX's organic and paid positions.\n\n### 3. Conversion Rate Decline (−31%)\n- Phase 1 conversion rate: **12.75%**\n- Phase 3 conversion rate: **8.81%**\n\nThis 31% drop means that for every 100 clicks received today, the product converts approximately 4 fewer customers than at launch. Combined with higher CPCs, the effective cost per order has increased substantially.\n\n### 4. Four Defensive Campaigns Launched in 21 Days (Apr 7–27)\nThe rapid addition of four new campaign types — video brand (SBV), product-view remarketing (SD VCPM), multi-product brand defense (SB), and category DSP (SD CAT) — within a three-week span is a strong signal that organic rankings were falling and the team was scrambling to maintain visibility:\n\n| Date | New Campaign Type | Signal |\n|---|---|---|\n| Apr 7 | Video brand campaign | Organic brand visibility declining |\n| Apr 11 | Product-view remarketing | Customers browsing but not buying |\n| Apr 19 | Multi-product brand | Cross-brand protection needed |\n| Apr 27 | Category DSP VCPM | Reach expansion to recapture lost category share |\n\n### 5. Remarketing ROAS of 1.25x (Conversion Problem)\nThe SD retargeting campaign (targeting people who already viewed B0D41ZMDPD) achieved only **1.25x ROAS** — barely above break-even. This indicates that even warm audiences who previously showed interest in the product are reluctant to purchase. This typically points to:\n- Price perception issue (competitors offering lower prices)\n- Review/rating deterioration\n- Listing quality decline (outdated images, insufficient A+ content)\n\n### 6. Competitor Targeting Campaign Failed and Was Abandoned\nThe campaign **SBV-T1 MAX-竞品-ASIN-横板-solder** (targeting competitor ASINs) ran only 22 days (Mar 9 – Mar 30) with just **$3 spend and $0 attributed sales**. It was subsequently abandoned, suggesting competitor product pages are too well-defended or that T1 MAX does not win when placed alongside competitors.\n\n---\n\n## Root Cause Summary\n\n| Cause | Evidence | Impact |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Increased keyword competition** | CPC up 33% ($1.40 → $1.86), competitor targeting failed | Reduced impression share, higher acquisition cost |\n| **Declining conversion rate** | Conv. rate fell from 12.75% to 8.81% | Each click delivers less revenue |\n| **Organic rank pressure** | 4 defensive campaigns launched in 3 weeks | Less free traffic; more dependency on paid ads |\n| **Price/listing competitiveness** | Remarketing ROAS only 1.25x (warm audience not converting) | Product not compelling enough vs. alternatives |\n| **Market demand softening** | Category-level DSP added to broaden reach (lower efficiency) | Fewer high-intent buyers in the funnel |\n\n---\n\n## Quantitative Snapshot\n\n| Metric | Phase 1 (SP Core) | Phase 3 (Defensive) | Change |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| ROAS | 5.59x | 2.89x | −48% |\n| CPC | $1.40 | $1.86 | +33% |\n| Conv. Rate | 12.75% | 8.81% | −31% |\n| Campaign count | 4 | 4 (new additions) | Defensive escalation |\n| Est. daily ad spend (T1 MAX total) | ~$625/day | +$91/day incremental | Spend growing to offset decline |\n\n---\n\n## Recommendations\n\n1. **Audit the product listing**: Review star ratings, Q&A, images, and A+ content. The 1.25x remarketing ROAS suggests listing quality or price is the conversion barrier.\n2. **Price check vs. competitors**: Run a category competitive pricing analysis. The failed competitor targeting campaign suggests T1 MAX may be losing on price.\n3. **Optimize core SP campaigns**: Review keyword-level bid reports for KW-A and KW-B to identify wasted spend on low-converting search terms.\n4. **Pause low-ROAS campaigns**: The SBV video campaign (1.85x) and SD VCPM remarketing (1.25x) are burning spend below acceptable ROAS thresholds — consider pausing or restructuring.\n5. **Investigate review velocity**: Check if negative reviews have appeared post-launch that are suppressing conversion rates.\n"
