          "content": "# EV163: 8-Week Ad Type Spend Mix Analysis\n\n## Weekly Spend by Ad Type (Mar 13 - May 7, 2026)\n\n| Week | Dates | SP Spend | SB Spend | SD Spend | Total | SP % | SB % | SD % |\n|------|-------|----------|----------|----------|-------|------|------|------|\n| 1 | Mar 13-19 | $6,326 | $375 | $0 | $6,702 | **94.4%** | 5.6% | 0% |\n| 2 | Mar 20-26 | $6,646 | $375 | $0 | $7,020 | **94.7%** | 5.3% | 0% |\n| 3 | Mar 27-Apr 2 | $6,272 | $231 | $0 | $6,503 | **96.4%** | 3.6% | 0% |\n| 4 | Apr 3-9 | $8,264 | $356 | $0 | $8,620 | **95.9%** | 4.1% | 0% |\n| 5 | Apr 10-16 | $14,018 | $755 | $0 | $14,773 | **94.9%** | 5.1% | 0% |\n| 6 | Apr 17-23 | $12,792 | $451 | $0 | $13,244 | **96.6%** | 3.4% | 0% |\n| 7 | Apr 24-30 | $10,567 | $385 | $0 | $10,953 | **96.5%** | 3.5% | 0% |\n| 8 | May 1-7 | $11,928 | $457 | $0 | $12,386 | **96.3%** | 3.7% | 0% |\n\n## Mix Shift Analysis\n\n### Overall Trend: Stable Mix with Minor Fluctuations\n\n**Sponsored Products (SP): 94-97%**\n- Average: **95.7%** of total spend\n- Range: 94.4% - 96.6%\n- Variance: 2.2 percentage points\n- **Status**: Dominant, stable\n\n**Sponsored Brands (SB): 3-6%**\n- Average: **4.3%** of total spend\n- Range: 3.4% - 5.6%\n- Variance: 2.2 percentage points\n- **Status**: Minor, fluctuating\n\n**Sponsored Display (SD): 0%**\n- **Not running** any SD campaigns\n- Opportunity for diversification\n\n### Detailed Trend Analysis\n\n**Phase 1: March (Weeks 1-3)**\n- SP: 94.4% → 96.4% (+2.0%)\n- SB: 5.6% → 3.6% (-2.0%)\n- **Direction**: Shifting toward SP\n\n**Phase 2: Early April (Weeks 4-5)**\n- SP: 95.9% → 94.9% (-1.0%)\n- SB: 4.1% → 5.1% (+1.0%)\n- **Direction**: Slight shift toward SB\n\n**Phase 3: Late April-May (Weeks 6-8)**\n- SP: 96.6% → 96.3% (-0.3%)\n- SB: 3.4% → 3.7% (+0.3%)\n- **Direction**: Relatively stable\n\n## Verdict: NO SIGNIFICANT SHIFT\n\n### Evidence\n\n**1. Narrow Range**\n- SP variance: Only 2.2 percentage points (94.4-96.6%)\n- SB variance: Only 2.2 percentage points (3.4-5.6%)\n- Too small to indicate strategic shift\n\n**2. No Clear Direction**\n- First 4 weeks: SP avg 95.3%, SB avg 4.7%\n- Last 4 weeks: SP avg 96.1%, SB avg 3.9%\n- **Change**: SP +0.8%, SB -0.8% (minimal)\n\n**3. Absolute Spend Correlation**\n- SB spend correlates with total spend\n- Week 5 (highest total $14.8K): SB = $755 (5.1%)\n- Week 3 (lowest total $6.5K): SB = $231 (3.6%)\n- **Insight**: SB scales with total budget, not strategic reallocation\n\n**4. Consistent Strategy**\n- SP remains dominant across all 8 weeks\n- SB maintains minor supporting role\n- No SD investment throughout period\n\n## Absolute Spend Trends\n\n### Sponsored Products (SP)\n| Period | Avg Weekly SP Spend | Trend |\n|--------|---------------------|-------|\n| Weeks 1-4 | $6,877 | Baseline |\n| Weeks 5-8 | $12,326 | **+79% increase** ⬆️ |\n\n**SP is scaling significantly** in absolute terms\n\n### Sponsored Brands (SB)\n| Period | Avg Weekly SB Spend | Trend |\n|--------|---------------------|-------|\n| Weeks 1-4 | $334 | Baseline |\n| Weeks 5-8 | $512 | **+53% increase** ⬆️ |\n\n**SB is also scaling** but at slower rate than SP\n\n### Key Insight\nBoth ad types are scaling, but SP is growing faster:\n- SP growth: +79%\n- SB growth: +53%\n- **Result**: Mix shifts slightly toward SP (95.3% → 96.1%)\n\n## Implications\n\n### Current Strategy Assessment\n\n**Strengths:**\n- ✅ SP dominance is appropriate (highest ROI typically)\n- ✅ Consistent strategy execution\n- ✅ Both ad types scaling together\n\n**Weaknesses:**\n- ❌ SB underutilized (only 4% of spend)\n- ❌ SD completely absent (0% spend)\n- ❌ Limited diversification\n\n### Comparison to Industry Benchmarks\n\n**Typical Ad Mix for Established Brands:**\n- SP: 70-80% (current: 96%) - **Over-indexed**\n- SB: 15-25% (current: 4%) - **Under-indexed**\n- SD: 5-10% (current: 0%) - **Missing**\n\n**Current mix is heavily SP-focused**\n\n## Recommendations\n\n### Immediate Actions\n\n**1. Increase SB Investment**\n- **Current**: $400-500/week (4%)\n- **Target**: $1,500-2,000/week (15%)\n- **Rationale**: SB drives brand awareness and top-of-funnel traffic\n\n**2. Launch SD Campaigns**\n- **Target**: $500-800/week (5%)\n- **Focus**: Remarketing to site visitors\n- **Expected**: Lower ACOS than SP, good for conversions\n\n**3. Rebalance Mix**\n- **Target allocation**:\n  - SP: 75-80% (down from 96%)\n  - SB: 15-20% (up from 4%)\n  - SD: 5-10% (new)\n\n### Strategic Recommendations\n\n**Sponsored Products (SP) - Maintain Dominance**\n- Continue as primary driver\n- Current spend level: $10-14K/week\n- Focus on efficiency (reduce ACOS from current 19-21%)\n\n**Sponsored Brands (SB) - Scale Up**\n- **Week 9 target**: $1,000 (double current)\n- **Week 12 target**: $2,000 (4x current)\n- **Use cases**:\n  - Brand defense keywords\n  - Category keywords for awareness\n  - Competitor conquesting\n  - Video ads for engagement\n\n**Sponsored Display (SD) - Launch**\n- **Week 9**: Launch with $500/week\n- **Targeting strategies**:\n  - Views remarketing (retarget site visitors)\n  - Product targeting (competitor ASINs)\n  - Audience targeting (in-market shoppers)\n- **Expected ACOS**: 15-20% (better than current SP)\n\n### Implementation Timeline\n\n**Week 9 (Immediate):**\n- Increase SB budget to $1,000/week\n- Launch SD remarketing campaign ($500/week)\n- Maintain SP at $10-12K/week\n\n**Week 10-12 (Ramp Up):**\n- SB: Scale to $1,500-2,000/week\n- SD: Scale to $800-1,000/week\n- SP: Optimize for efficiency, maintain spend\n\n**Week 13+ (Steady State):**\n- SP: 75-80% ($12-14K/week)\n- SB: 15-20% ($2.5-3.5K/week)\n- SD: 5-10% ($1-1.5K/week)\n- **Total**: $15.5-19K/week\n\n## Expected Impact\n\n**After rebalancing (12 weeks):**\n\n**Diversification Benefits:**\n- Reduced reliance on SP (96% → 78%)\n- Multiple traffic sources\n- Better brand awareness (SB)\n- Improved remarketing (SD)\n\n**Performance Improvements:**\n- Overall ACOS: Improve by 2-3% (SD/SB typically more efficient)\n- Sales: Increase 15-20% from expanded reach\n- New-to-brand: Increase 30-40% (SB drives new customers)\n\n**Risk Mitigation:**\n- Less vulnerable to SP algorithm changes\n- Diversified traffic sources\n- Better full-funnel coverage\n\n## Conclusion\n\n**Current State**: Mix is stable with no significant shift over 8 weeks. SP dominates at 96%, SB at 4%, SD absent.\n\n**Assessment**: Mix is **too heavily weighted toward SP**. While SP should be dominant, current 96% allocation leaves opportunities on the table.\n\n**Recommendation**: Gradually rebalance to 75% SP / 20% SB / 5% SD over next 12 weeks for better diversification and performance.\n\n**Priority**: Launch SD campaigns immediately (biggest gap) and scale SB investment (currently underutilized).\n"
