          "label": "Sonnet 4.6",
          "content": "# Account-Level ACOS: Last 30 Days vs. Prior 30 Days\n\n**Account:** Firefly Buys  \n**Last 30 days:** 2026-04-08 – 2026-05-07  \n**Prior 30 days:** 2026-03-09 – 2026-04-07  \n**Report rows:** 148 (last 30), 150 (prior 30)  \n**Currency:** USD\n\n---\n\n## 1. Headline ACOS Movement\n\n| Metric | Prior 30 | Last 30 | Change |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Total Spend | $30,072.70 | $54,354.33 | +$24,281.63 (+80.7%) |\n| Total Sales | $192,488.74 | $275,236.90 | +$82,748.16 (+43.0%) |\n| **Account ACOS** | **15.62%** | **19.75%** | **+4.13 pp** |\n| Impressions | 3,144,782 | 5,642,649 | +79.4% |\n| Clicks | 25,556 | 40,332 | +57.8% |\n| Purchases | 5,199 | 5,728 | +10.2% |\n\nACOS worsened by **4.13 percentage points** despite both spend and sales growing. The core problem: spend scaled at nearly twice the rate of sales (+80.7% vs +43.0%).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Spend vs. Sales Decomposition\n\nUsing a two-factor sequential decomposition (hold-one-vary-one):\n\n| Effect | Impact on ACOS |\n|---|---:|\n| Spend increase alone (holding sales at prior-period level) | **+12.61 pp** |\n| Sales increase (partially offsetting) | **−8.49 pp** |\n| **Net ACOS change** | **+4.13 pp** |\n\nInterpretation: Spend nearly doubled while sales grew by only 43%. The sales growth was not proportional enough to absorb the spend expansion, leaving a net 4.13 pp ACOS deterioration.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Compositional Shift (Ad Product Mix)\n\n| Ad Product | Prior Spend Share | Last Spend Share | Prior ACOS | Last ACOS | ACOS Δ |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n| Sponsored Products | 95.2% | 96.1% | 15.85% | 20.43% | +4.58 pp |\n| Sponsored Brands | 4.8% | 3.9% | 12.14% | 10.84% | −1.30 pp |\n\n**Mix shift effect: +0.09 pp** (negligible — the small shift toward higher-ACOS SP was nearly imperceptible at the account level).\n\n**Within-product ACOS change effect: +4.04 pp** (virtually the entire ACOS increase came from SP performing worse, not from a mix shift).\n\nThe compositional story is almost entirely about **Sponsored Products deteriorating in efficiency** (+4.58 pp), not about budget moving between channels.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Campaign-Level Contributors (Sponsored Products)\n\nRanked by contribution to account-level ACOS change (Δspend/total_sales):\n\n| Campaign | Prior ACOS | Last ACOS | ACOS Contrib |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| **GPS-GPetShop_Cool_Pet_Pad-MULTI-NB-SP-Exact** | 16.0% | 21.4% | **+2.30 pp** |\n| GPS-GPetShop_Cool_Pet_Pad-MULTI-NB-SP-Phrase | 17.0% | 20.0% | +1.44 pp |\n| GPS-Chillz_Pet_Pad-MULTI-NB-SP-Exact | 17.8% | 24.9% | +0.74 pp |\n| Hornady-Fireproof_Safe-B09T… (new) | N/A | 32.6% | +0.59 pp |\n| Hornady-RAPiD_Gun_Safes-NB-Phrase | 25.8% | 108.4% | +0.48 pp |\n| GPS-GPetShop_Cool_Pet_Pad-Branded-Phrase | 5.9% | 7.2% | +0.48 pp |\n| Petkin-BigNThick_Pet_Wipes-Branded | 15.7% | 19.7% | −0.73 pp (offset) |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Single Biggest Contributor\n\n**GPS-GPetShop_Cool_Pet_Pad-MULTI-NB-SP-Exact** is the single biggest contributor to the ACOS increase, responsible for **+2.30 pp** of the 4.13 pp total swing. Its ACOS moved from 16.0% to 21.4% while its absolute spend scaled up significantly, making it the largest drag. The sibling phrase-match campaign (GPS-GPetShop_Cool_Pet_Pad-MULTI-NB-SP-Phrase) contributed a further +1.44 pp, meaning the GPetShop Cool Pet Pad non-branded SP group collectively accounts for **+3.74 pp** — nearly 91% of the total ACOS deterioration.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Reasoning Summary\n\n| Root Cause | Mechanism | ACOS Impact |\n|---|---|---:|\n| Spend scale-up outpaced sales growth | 80.7% spend growth vs 43.0% sales growth | Primary driver |\n| SP ACOS degradation | Non-branded SP campaigns spent more at worse conversion efficiency | +4.04 pp of 4.13 pp |\n| Mix shift (SP vs SB) | Negligible | +0.09 pp |\n| **Biggest single campaign** | GPetShop Cool Pet Pad NB Exact: spend scaled, ACOS 16→21% | **+2.30 pp** |\n\nThe account is in an aggressive spend expansion phase. The efficiency loss is concentrated in non-branded Sponsored Products — specifically the GPetShop Cool Pet Pad product line — where increased bid/budget did not produce proportionally more sales.\n"
