          "label": "Opus 4.7",
          "content": "# Hero ASINs vs. Long Tail — Who Moves Account ACOS?\n\n## Data window\n- Last 30 days (recent): 2026-04-08 → 2026-05-07.\n- Rows: 148 campaigns, 949 product × campaign.\n- Spend is allocated to ASINs by proportional attribution (ASIN sales share within each campaign × campaign spend).\n\n## Top 10 \"hero\" ASINs by allocated spend\n\n| ASIN | Spend | Sales | ACOS |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| B006NONHNE | $3,321 | $20,481 | **16%** |\n| B081DK7DQH | $3,135 | $6,570 | **48%** |\n| B09TQ2CW9L | $2,898 | $10,813 | 27% |\n| B0C5MYTF7W | $2,522 | $15,519 | 16% |\n| B006NOO440 | $1,925 | $12,476 | 15% |\n| B07XPGKJKM | $1,881 | $11,833 | 16% |\n| B0G2YJ9KK2 | $1,862 | $11,830 | 16% |\n| B0C5MY7MNL | $1,761 | $11,151 | 16% |\n| B0G2Y26PSL | $1,730 | $12,230 | 14% |\n| B0C5N3713P | $1,340 | $8,783 | 15% |\n| **Hero total** | **$22,373** | **$121,686** | **18%** |\n\nHero share of account ad spend: **41.3%**.\n\n## Long tail (the other ~300 ASINs)\n\n| | Spend | Sales | ACOS |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Long tail (everything outside top 10) | $31,809 | $160,235 | **20%** |\n\n## Who is moving account ACOS?\n\n### Concentration of spend\n- Hero ASINs: 41.3% of account spend.\n- Long tail: 58.7% of account spend.\n- Account blended ACOS: **19.7%** (= 54,182 / 281,921).\n\n### Efficiency comparison\n- Hero ACOS: **18%** (roughly 2 pp better than blended).\n- Long tail ACOS: **20%** (roughly 0.3 pp worse than blended).\n\n**The long tail is pulling account ACOS up; heroes are pulling it down.** But the long tail is also ~1.4× the spend of heroes, so its dollar impact on account-level movement is larger.\n\n### Movement decomposition (hypothetical — which cohort is more responsible if account ACOS changes)\n- For heroes to push account ACOS up by 1 pp, their ACOS would need to worsen by ~2.4 pp (from 18% to 20.4%).\n- For long tail to push account ACOS up by 1 pp, their ACOS would need to worsen by ~1.7 pp (from 20% to 21.7%).\n\nThe long tail is **more leveraged** (smaller ACOS move → bigger account impact), because they're bigger spend.\n\n### Inside the hero list — B081DK7DQH is the outlier\nHornady's B081DK7DQH sits at **48% ACOS** while every other hero is at 14–27%. If B081DK7DQH's ACOS alone went from 48% to 20%, the hero cohort's blended ACOS would fall from 18% to ~13.5%, moving account blended ACOS by ~0.9 pp. **Single ASIN contribution at that magnitude matters.**\n\n## Answer\n- **Long-tail ASINs carry more of the account's ACOS movement** by virtue of being 58.7% of the spend.\n- **But within heroes, B081DK7DQH is a disproportionate drag** — one hero ASIN at 48% ACOS is doing more damage than several long-tail ASINs.\n\n## Recommendation\n1. **Focus optimization on B081DK7DQH** first. 48% ACOS on $3K spend is the single highest-leverage hero fix.\n2. **Audit the long tail in groups** — with 300+ ASINs in the tail, a sweep (e.g., \"any ASIN with ACOS > 30% and spend > $50\") is the right approach, not per-ASIN.\n3. **The healthy heroes (B006NONHNE, B0C5MYTF7W, B006NOO440, B07XPGKJKM, B0G2YJ9KK2, B0C5MY7MNL, B0G2Y26PSL, B0C5N3713P)** are all in the 14–16% ACOS band. These support scaling — consider lifting their budgets together.\n\n## What I still don't have\n- **Prior-period equivalent decomposition** — to answer \"who moved the account's ACOS\" over a specific period of change rather than just in steady state.\n- **ASIN-level ACOS trend per week** — to tell which hero/long-tail ASINs are trending up or down.\n- **Brand/category tags per ASIN** — to aggregate long tail meaningfully.\n- **B081DK7DQH's keyword-level data** — to identify what specifically is driving its 48% ACOS.\n- **Campaign-to-ASIN share detail** — the proportional allocation I used is an approximation; actual per-ASIN spend would require ad-level reports.\n"
